{"key":"processedPost-10188539","value":{"id":10188539,"first":10100821,"last":11768477,"when":1240062616,"utime":"04/18/09 04:50 PM","content":"If you vacuum seal the bags, you won't be able to insert a thermometer into the center of the substrate, thus you won't know when you've reached pasteurization temp.<br /><br />I pasteurize in filter patch bags all the time, but leave them unsealed.&nbsp; Your cooler idea won't work.&nbsp; You want the center of your substrate <i>within</i> the bags to be at 140F to 160F for an hour.&nbsp; If you had them in 160F water, I doubt they'd reach that temp even if you left them for 12 hours.<br /><br />Load your bags and put them in large pots of water on the stove.&nbsp; Use your stove burner to regulate the temp in the center of the bags, and keep them in the range stated above.<br />RR","title":"Re: bulk vacuum pasturize."}}